Reviews associated with stopped repositories fail to load with an exception:
{code}
Your request was unable to be processed
javax.servlet.ServletException - javax.el.ELException: java.lang.NullPointerException
{code}
The stacktrace on the server includes:
{code}
 Caused by: java.lang.NullPointerException
      	at com.cenqua.crucible.util.SourceUtils.isGit(SourceUtils.java:15)
      	at com.cenqua.crucible.view.FRXNavList.getSourceNode(FRXNavList.java:216)

{code}

Listener plugin modules that are listening for ReviewCreatedEvents are unable to determine the creator of created reviews.

{code}
@EventListener
public void onReviewCreatedEvent(final ReviewCreatedEvent event) {
    final PermId<ReviewData> reviewId = event.getReviewId();
    final ReviewData review = reviewService.getReview(reviewId);
    review.getCreator(); // returns null
}
{code}

Linking to a git changeset requires an unfortunate amount of typing, since you have to specify both the changeset ID and the repository name:
{code}
{cs:id=9c3c803c10b9b973abf7fa9bfa906d9180fcdc4e|repo=atlassian-oauth}
{code}

Even if it's possible for a code review to include changes from more than one repository, most reviews do not. It'd be nice if the {{cs}} macro were smart enough to know what the default repo name should be.

This creates errors when accessing Crucible over HTTPS, in IE and other browsers, where the browser warns that there is mixed HTTP and HTTPS resources in the page.

*Workarounds:*

# Each user can disable the IDE Connector by navigating to {{Profile Settings >> Display Settings >> IDE Connector}} and setting {{Enable IDE icons}} to {{No}}.
# Connect to the underlying database and run the following SQL statement in order to disable the IDE icons to all users at once:
{code:sql}
update cru_user_profile set cru_enableide = false;
{code}

In Python, a tabulation makes the difference between being inside or outside of a statement.

*Steps to reproduce the problem:*
# Download and commit the Python file attached in a Git repository;
# Download the patch attached;
# Create a pre-commit review with the patch file;
# Crucible will show diffs when having the view set to "Full Context" + "Show All Whitespace" - correct behavior.
# Crucible won't show any diffs when having the view set to "Full Context" + "Hide Insignificant Whitespace" - incorrect behavior, because the whitespace Crucible hid *were indeed significant* considering this is a Python file.

*NOTE:* If the patch isn't anchored, or not viewing the full context, then you'll see the diffs.

Clicking on "Administration" -> Users, the following error is displayed:

{code}
User Agent: Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 8.0; Windows NT 5.1; Trident/4.0; .NET CLR 1.1.4322; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; .NET CLR 3.0.4506.2152; .NET CLR 3.5.30729; InfoPath.2; .NET4.0C)
Timestamp: Tue, 18 Oct 2011 05:54:05 UTC

Message: Object doesn't support this property or method
Line: 32
Char: 13
Code: 0
URI: http://crucible-dev.goharvey.com.au/static/lrss5f/admin.js
{code}

We're using a feature that IE8 doesn't supportin admin.js:
{code}
        AJS.$(".checkTrailingWhiteSpace").each(function() {
            var text = AJS.$(this).text();
            if (text != text.trim()) {
                AJS.$(this).addClass("trailingWhiteSpace");
                showWhiteSpaceWarning = true;
            }
        });
{code}
The trim is the problem. We should use jQuery's trim instead.

The problem code for that one is when GWT does this:
{code}
function __gwt_initWindowCloseHandler(beforeunload, unload) {
  var wnd = window
  , oldOnBeforeUnload = wnd.onbeforeunload
  , oldOnUnload = wnd.onunload;
  
  wnd.onbeforeunload = function(evt) {
    var ret, oldRet;
    try {
      ret = beforeunload();
    } finally {
      oldRet = oldOnBeforeUnload && oldOnBeforeUnload(evt);
    }
    // Avoid returning null as IE6 will coerce it into a string.
    // Ensure that "" gets returned properly.
    if (ret != null) {
      return ret;
    }
    if (oldRet != null) {
      return oldRet;
    }
    // returns undefined.
  };
  
  wnd.onunload = function(evt) {
    try {
      unload();
    } finally {
      oldOnUnload && oldOnUnload(evt);
      wnd.onresize = null;
      wnd.onscroll = null;
      wnd.onbeforeunload = null;
      wnd.onunload = null;
    }
  };
  
  // Remove the reference once we've initialize the handler
  wnd.__gwt_initWindowCloseHandler = undefined;
}
{code}
oldOnBeforeUnload is a jQuery function, evt is undefined, and jQuery flips out
would have to spend some time on it to figure out how to fix jQuery

